The goal is:
`⊢ Prod.fst <$>
      ((simulateQ loggingOracle).toFun (pSpec.FullTranscript × StmtOut × WitOut)
          (@Prover.run ι oSpec StmtIn StmtOut WitIn WitOut n pSpec stmt wit prover)).run =
    @Prover.run ι oSpec StmtIn StmtOut WitIn WitOut n pSpec stmt wit prover`

We need to show that applying `Prod.fst` to the result of `((simulateQ ...).toFun ...).run` gives `@Prover.run ...`.

Looking at the types:
- `((simulateQ ...).toFun ...).run` has type `(pSpec.FullTranscript × StmtOut × WitOut) × (QueryLog ...)` because `((simulateQ ...).toFun ...)` is a function that takes a term of type `(pSpec.FullTranscript × StmtOut × WitOut)` and returns a term of type `((pSpec.FullTranscript × StmtOut × WitOut) × (QueryLog ...))`. When we apply this function to `@Prover.run ...` (which is of type `(pSpec.FullTranscript × StmtOut × WitOut)`), the result is `⟨@Prover.run ..., some_log⟩`.
- `Prod.fst` applied to `⟨@Prover.run ..., some_log⟩` yields `@Prover.run ...`.

This matches the right side of the equality. So the theorem is correct.

